[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I am sure it will not be your last. Thank you for coming here. We are looking at statutory instruments, and we have an excellent set of questions prepared by the 
[normal]Clerks 
[normal]of the Committee
[normal].
[normal] I am not going to waste any time, because we do not have a lot of time. What prompted the Hansard Society to look into delegated legislation? What is it you were expecting to find?
[normal]Dr Fox[bold]: What prompted it 
[normal]were
[normal] two previous studies that we had done looking at legislative process
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]In the interests of transparency, I should say that that research and this research was funded by the Nuffield Foundation. 
[normal]From
[normal] those two studies of the legislative process, it became clear that delegated legislation was an issue that had not been looked at to any great extent in recent years
[normal]. I
[normal]t 
[normal]was 
[normal]also an area of growing concern 
[normal]because of
[normal] the volume, the complexity and the expansion of the number of scrutiny methods and mechanisms that were, at present, concerned about Henry VIII powers.
[normal]With Joel as our lead researcher on the project
[normal], what we have done over a two-year period 
[normal]is look at six case studies
[normal]:
[normal] three Bills in this Parliament and three Bills in the previous Parliament. We have deliberately looked at controversial elements
[normal]: at where 
[normal]there were concerns about Henry VIII, about the conferring of powers and 
[normal]about 
[normal]the scrutiny mechanisms. We have looked at those Bills through the life cycle
[normal],
[normal] beginning in 
[normal]Whitehall
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Our 
[normal]concern is not just what happens here in terms of scrutiny, but what happens upstream in Whitehall in terms of the decision to make the separation between primary and secondary, and then also the drafting and handling process upstream in Whitehall
[normal],
[normal] and the impact that has, as well as what happens 
[normal]then 
[normal]when it arrives in the Commons and the Lords.
[normal]Our concern throughout has been to think about
[normal] h
[normal]ow you deal with the most controversial and the most difficult elements of the system, and what that 
[normal]then 
[normal]tell
[normal]s
[normal] us about how we might reform the process to address those difficulties and separate out the less controversial, day-to-day statutory instruments and delegat
[normal]ed legislat
[normal]ion from the controversial, and make sure that Parliament is looking at what Parliament wants and needs to look at,
[normal] given the deluge of delegation.
