[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Nuttall:[bold] Yes. Before we turn to Henry VIII clauses, while you have been conducting the research so far, have you come across any specific examples of where the procedure that is being followed for SIs has been inappropriate?
[normal]Joel Blackwell[bold]: There was one case with the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006 and the orders that came about from those. 
[normal]Do 
[normal]you know about the process
[normal]? The 
[normal]Government decides and lets the 
[normal]Committee 
[normal]know what procedure it prefers and what it thinks it should be scrutinised at
[normal]. O
[normal]ne of the particular orders was a negative procedure in the Government’s eyes, 
[normal]but
[normal] the Lords Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee
[normal] 
[normal]decided to upgrade that to a super-affirmative procedure, which is quite a giant leap in terms of 
[normal]Committee 
[normal]procedures.
[normal]I think it goes back to the point that we were making at the beginning in terms of leaving it to gut feeling 
[normal]when
[normal] assigning a procedure, and the switch between the affirmative and the negative can lead to mistakes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Nuttall:[bold] Turning to the Henry VIII powers, have you come across any examples where they have been used inappropriately while you have been doing this?
[normal]Dr Fox[bold]: In terms of the Bills we have looked at, 
[normal]there was the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act; 
[normal]the initial powers on the Bill were very, very wide
[normal]. You 
[normal]then 
[normal]have 
[normal]the inclusion of 
[normal]public bodies. I gave evidence just before Christmas on the 
[normal]d
[normal]raft Deregulation Bill, where there w
[normal]ere
[normal] very, very wide Henry VIII powers that I would regard as inappropriate in the context of what the Government was doing. 
[normal]T
[normal]he concern we have about Henry VIII powers—they are not always a bad thing, and I think there is an assumption now too much that perhaps every Henry VIII is wrong and we should not have any of them
[normal]—
[normal]is that the first instinct of the Government
[normal] is
[normal] to go to the Henry VIII and to do it through the delegation, whereas it ought to be the last stage if they have considered things like repeal consolidation, Law Commission and so on
[normal],
[normal] as options for revising the statute book. Too often it is a first resort and there are too many of them.
[normal]Joel Blackwell[bold]: Just to add to that, one of our objectives was to tell the story of delegated legislation throughout the last century
[normal],
[normal] the reform processes and the inquiries that have taken place on delegated legislation. Henry VIII powers were first raised in 1932 by the Donoughmore Committee
[normal]. T
[normal]hey said that they should be used only in exceptional cases and in times of emergency, so we are going over the same issues again and again. As Ruth rightly says, not all Henry VIII powers are bad, but three of the cases that we have seen were framework Bills. Three of them had some very wide powers. 
[normal]On introduction to the House of t
[normal]he Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 
[normal]in 
[normal]2006, the first clause was enabling the Minister by order to reform legislation
[normal].
[normal] I think there is a concern with academic
[normal]s and
[normal] people 
[normal]who are 
[normal]interested in this that we may have reached the bottom line and 
[normal]that 
[normal]the floodgates may have opened
[normal], and w
[normal]e are 
[normal]now 
[normal]seeing around 100 Henry VIII clauses appearing per 
[normal]Session
[normal].
[normal]Dr Fox[bold]: One of the concerns is
[normal]:
[normal] is the debate shifting in Parliament to focus on the scrutiny procedure to constrain the power, rather than the question of whether the power should be there in the first place? The Government has responded on the 
[normal]d
[normal]raft Deregulation Bill, and the 
[normal]final version of 
[normal]Bill that has 
[normal]been 
[normal]brought forward does not have those clauses in it. They have taken it out and responded to the pre-legislative scrutiny stage
[normal]. B
[normal]ut there is an awful lot of discussion now
[normal],
[normal] in terms of focusing on the Henry VIII 
[normal]powers, 
[normal]around
[normal], “H
[normal]ow do we constrain it with these enhanced or super-affirmatives?
[normal]”
[normal] The consequence of that is that the debate becomes more about the control of it, rather than the principle of whether it should be there in the first place. We have ended up in a situation where, because of the way the Government handles it and grants concessions
[normal]—
[normal]particularly in the Lords
[normal]—
[normal]around the enhanced and affirmative procedures to constrain the power, you are ending up with 
[normal]a
[normal] huge number of variations of scrutiny
[normal]. That is 
[normal]adding layer on layer of complexity and making it even more difficult for people, parliamentarians included, to understand, let alone anybody else outside. It goes back to the question of whether they should be there in the first place as opposed to the constant focus on the constraint.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Martin Vickers:[bold] The Lords have much more comprehensive SI scrutiny. Are there any examples of good and bad practice that you have come across that you can draw to our attention?
[normal]Joel Blackwell[bold]: The Delegated Powers Committee in particular
[normal]; 
[normal]there are some examples of good practice there. The reports are very good. I think there is a lot of respect for the recommendations made by the Committee, and the Government tends to accept them, although there are issues. Although the Committee is viewed by other jurisdictions as a benchmark for good practice, throughout our research we have noted things that could be improved, particularly with regard to talking about precedent when it comes to procedures. Also, there is significant variability in the delegated powers memorandum that is submitted by 
[normal]Departments 
[normal]to that Committee
[normal]. I think
[normal] the Committee is yet to really push and use the powers that they exercise to improve that in some cases. The other 
[normal]Committees 
[normal]as well
[normal]—
[normal]do you want to talk about those, Ruth?
[normal]Dr Fox[bold]: Yes. One of the things that the Lords 
[normal]have
[normal] done particularly well is to push the boundaries. I take the point that the Government wants its legislation through as quickly as possible, but the Lords Committees have been quite strong at pushing at the boundaries, first of all by Delegated Powers issuing its detailed guidance, which now is encompassed in the Cabinet Office 
[normal]Guide to Making Legislation
[normal]. 
[normal]Certainly all the Bill teams—when they are working on the Bills and developing them in the 
[normal]Departments
[normal]—have to make reference to that and use that as a guide to how they develop the Bill. 
[normal]As Joel says, the consequence of that is that there is often a consultation process with the Committee in advance before they move forward to try to avoid difficulties. 
[normal]Clearly t
[normal]hat is not perfect
[normal],
[normal] but it certainly helps. The consequence of that is that a lot of the recommendations of the Committee are adhered to.
[normal]The other 
[normal]Committee 
[normal]in the Lords where they pushed at the boundaries a few years ago—I think it was 20
[normal]06 or 2007—was the s
[normal]uper
[normal]-c
[normal]asino 
[normal]o
[normal]rder, where they took evidence for the first time on the reasons why 
[normal]Manchester
[normal] had been chosen over 
[normal]Blackpool
[normal]. I think that occasionally pushing at the boundaries of their remit, stepping out a little bit and pushing the Government, has really changed how delegated legislation is dealt with in the Upper House. As Joel says, it is not perfect in the sense that we have found instances where the Delegated Powers Committee has missed things
[normal] that 
[normal]get either a lot of consideration in this House or
[normal],
[normal] indeed
[normal], in the Lords.
[normal]One of the interesting 
[normal]question
[normal]s for the Commons is
[normal] 
[normal]this:
[normal] while
[normal] the Delegated Powers reports are regarded as very useful, they only kick in on Lords starters to benefit this House. On a Commons starter, you do not get that information until it is in the Lords, and then it comes back
